              p.mb-4 Micrococcal Nuclease Sequencing (MNase-Seq) using Illumina short reads is a powerful technique for analyzing chromatin accessibility and nucleosome positioning across the genome. This method involves digesting chromatin with micrococcal nuclease, sequencing the resulting DNA fragments, and mapping the sequences to a reference genome.
              p.mb-4 Bioinformatics services I can provide from MNase-Seq data include:
              ul
                li Data preprocessing: <a href="#" data-bs-toggle="modal" data-bs-target="#portfolioModalQC" data-origin-modal="#portfolioModalMNaseSeq">Quality control</a>, filtering, and trimming of raw sequencing reads.
                li Read alignment: Mapping short reads to a reference genome.
                li Nucleosome positioning: Identifying nucleosome-bound regions of the genome.
                li Differential accessibility analysis: Comparing chromatin accessibility patterns between conditions.
                li Functional annotation: Annotating nucleosome-bound regions with genomic features and performing pathway enrichment analyses.
                li Integration with other omics data: Combining MNase-Seq data with other types of data (e.g., RNA-Seq, ChIP-Seq) for multi-omics analysis.
                li Custom pipeline development: Developing tailored bioinformatics pipelines for specific research questions.
                li Visualization: Creating visual representations of MNase-Seq data and results.
